Data Science Through Wikipedia Revision History

Brian Cherin

Wikipedia is home to millions of articles about subjects ranging from famous people to mathematical concepts to literary works. It's a great place to get a general picture of a new topic, or as a way to find scholarly sources relevant to a topic.

The most amazing thing about Wikipedia is that it is almost completely community-based! This means that volunteers are responsible for creating and improving the content served by Wikipedia. This is often a reason why Wikipedia is claimed to be an unreliable source in academic contexts. But without these volunteers, Wikipedia could not have as large of a scope as it does.

In this tutorial, we are going to be working with a dataset which describes all of the revisions made to Wikipedia articles up to the year 2008. We will walk through each step of the data science process: data processing, exploratory data analysis, machine learning, and considering insights gained.

Throughout this process, we will be building a functional tool that could help people who write Wikipedia articles - a website suggestion generator. This would be a tool that suggests websites to look at for relevant research, based on the category of the article they are writing. We will be using the power of machine learning (specifically, clustering based on category similarity) to enable this tool to be useful and efficient.

Let's get started! First, we'll need to acquire the dataset and take some steps to make sure it's ready for our use.

A look at the dataset¶

This is the source of the dataset that we will be using: https://snap.stanford.edu/data/wiki-meta.html. The dataset is in a file named "enwiki-20080103.main.bz2" and it is described as "Revisions in the main namespace".

This is the content that the dataset contains, according to the source of the dataset. It describes one revision that was made to an article on Wikipedia, and also includes general information about that specific article (such as the list of categories it belongs to, and the list of external websites that the article links to).

REVISION article_id rev_id article_title timestamp [ip:]username user_id CATEGORY list of categories IMAGE list of images (each listed as many times as it occurs) MAIN through OTHER cross-references to pages in other namespaces EXTERNAL hyperlinks to pages outside Wikipedia TEMPLATE list of all templates (each listed as many times as it occurs) COMMENT contains the comments as entered by the author MINOR whether the edit was marked as minor by the author TEXTDATA word count of revision's plain text

Here is an example of what one observation in the data set looks like. It is a set of thirteen lines describing one revision that was made to a Wikipedia article:

REVISION 286633 163590672 Pasteurellosis 2007-10-10T16:21:31Z ClarkFreifeld 778331 CATEGORY Diseases IMAGE MAIN Pneumonia Human Pasteurella Infection Animal Bacterium TALK USER USER_TALK OTHER Fr:Pasteurellose Ja:パスツレラ症 EXTERNAL http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm/bc/121210.htm TEMPLATE Disease-stub Bacterial_diseases DiseaseDisorder_infobox COMMENT French precedes Japanese MINOR 1 TEXTDATA 50

Before we are reading to import the data into Python, we will need to do some pre-processing to the data.

Data pre-processing¶

If we wanted to use the entire dataset, that would require us to import 8.7 gigabytes worth of information into memory! That definitely isn't practical for our (educational) purposes, as it would take very long to do all of our operations (not to mention to simply import the data).

So, we are instead going to work with only a subset of the data. To be sure that all the data is equally represented in the subset we create, we are going to take a simple random sample of the data file.

To do so, we will iterate over the file, looking at the chunks of 14 lines at a time (the thirteen lines of the data for one observation, followed by one empty line). Then, we will generate a random number to decide if we are going to use this observation of the data, or skip over it. Then, we'll save all of the data that we chose into its own file, and import this file into Python to work with.

Using AWK to take a random sample¶

In order to efficiently perform this pre-processing on the data, we are going to use the UNIX command line tool called AWK. AWK allows us to create a mini-program that defines how we want to iterate over the file, and what operations we want to do to the data. In our case, we will simply be generating a random number to make a decision, and then printing out a group of lines based on that decision.

Here's a place where you can learn more about writing an AWK script: https://www.tutorialspoint.com/awk/index.htm

I won't go into any more detail about how to use AWK, since this tutorial will be focusing on Python code. But here's the AWK script we will be using to pre-process the data file. We will be taking a random sample so that we choose a subset of approximately 0.1% of the original dataset. This will shrink the file size to about 80 megabytes, which will be much more manageable to load into Python.

The AWK script:

function shouldUseChunk() {return (100*rand() < 0.1)} # A function to make a decision whether to use a group of lines or not BEGIN {line = 0; shouldPrintLine = 1; srand()} # These instructions are executed one time, at the start of execution { if (line % 14 == 0) { shouldPrintLine = shouldUseChunk() }; # At the start of each chunk, we decide whether to keep it if (shouldPrintLine) {print}; # If we decided to keep this chunk, output this line line++; # Keep track of the line index, so we can know when we reach the 14th line }

Creating our final data file¶

There's two more command line tools that we need to use -- bzcat and bzip2. Bzcat is used to extract the information stored by a bz2 archive file, allowing us to read from the original data file (which has the file type '.bz2'). Bzip2 will allow us to re-compress the data once we have processed it. We want to re-compress the data both to save space, and also to show the steps we would take in Python if we wanted to load the original data file without pre-processing.

Now, we will apply this AWK script to our data, and save the resulting file in a new compressed archive. The AWK script from above is stored in the file named awk_random_chunks.awk, and we want the final output to go to a file named wiki_point1percent.bz2.

bzcat enwiki-20080103.main.bz2 | awk -f awk_random_chunks.awk | bzip2 > wiki_point1percent.bz2

Once that's done, we finally have the data file that we are going to use! We now need to import it into Python. In the data file, each observation is represented by thirteen consecutive lines. We are going to parse the file and combine the information in those thirteen lines into a data structure, so that the information related to each observation is grouped together.

file = bz2.BZ2File('wiki_point1percent.bz2', 'r') # Import the file

all_data = []

more_lines = True
while more_lines: # Until we have reached the end of the data
    lines = islice(file, 14) # Read in 14 lines at a time (thirteen fields, plus one empty line)
    
    more_lines = False # Stop reading if there are no lines in this chunk
    
    data_row = {} # Initialize the dictionary to hold this observation's fields
    
    line_number = 0
    for line in lines: # Look at each line related to this observation
        line = line.decode('utf-8')
        more_lines = True # We see a line, so we keep reading the file after this point

        # Extract the field name and value from this line
        property_name = line.split(" ")[0]
        property_value = line[len(property_name):-1] # Take the rest of the line, ignoring the newline character at the end

        # Some values are empty, so only add the ones that have a value
        if len(property_value) > 0:
            data_row[property_name] = property_value
                
        line_number += 1
                        
    if more_lines: # Only append if this was a full set of lines
        all_data.append(data_row)

# Construct a DataFrame from the data
df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(all_data)
df.describe()

Tidying the data¶

Now that we've imported our data and loaded it into a DataFrame, we need to do some further processing so that the data is easy to work with and so that we will be able to do common Pandas operations.

We will take some steps to make the dataset more "tidy". You can read about what makes a dataset "tidy" here: https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/tidyr/vignettes/tidy-data.html

One concept of a tidy dataset means that each column should represent exactly one variable. The "revision" column of our dataset violates this, since it stores multiple different pieces of information. The first thing we will do is modify this so that each different value is placed in its own column.

According to the dataset description (https://snap.stanford.edu/data/wiki-meta.html), the "Revision" column represents:

article_id rev_id article_title timestamp [ip:]username user_id

To make this tidy, we will iterate over every row in the dataset and extract each individual part of the revision field. We will assign the values to their appropriate columns, specifically: article_id, revision_id, article_title, timestamp, and user_id.

In [6]:
for index, row in df.iterrows():
    
    # Extract the different data points from the "REVISION" column
    revision_string = row["REVISION"]
    parts = str(revision_string).split() # Split up into the individual strings

    df.at[index, "article_id"] = parts[0]
    df.at[index, "revision_id"] = parts[1]
    df.at[index, "article_title"] = parts[2]
    df.at[index, "user_id"] = parts[5]
    
    # Turn the timestamp into datetime object
    timestamp = parts[3]
    dt = datetime.strptime(timestamp, "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ")
    df.at[index, "timestamp"] = dt
    
    # Convert the "MINOR" column into a boolean
    df.at[index, "MINOR"] = int(row["MINOR"]) == 1

We will also make some small changes, dropping columns that we do not need, and renaming the "textdata" column to "words_revised".

Exploring the distribution of revisions¶

Each observation in this dataset represents one revision that was made to a Wikipedia page. Since we have the timestamp of each revision, me might be interested in learning about the distribution of revisions over time. Meaning, is there a certain time of day, day of the week, or month of the year that receives more revisions than others? We might also be interested in seeing if the amount of words modified in the revision has such a relationship with these units of time.

We can start by plotting the number of revisions over the hour of the day, day of week, and month of the year.

In [12]:
# Add columns representing the hour, day, and month that each revision was made, so it's easier to plot them
df["hour"] = df['timestamp'].apply(lambda x : x.hour)
df["day"] = df['timestamp'].apply(lambda x : x.weekday())
df["month"] = df['timestamp'].apply(lambda x : x.month)

In the above plot of hour of day versus number of revisions, there is a clear dip in number of revisions made from the 5th to the 12th hour. The timestamps for this dataset are in UTC time, having been provided in the ISO 8601 timestamp format. Converting to eastern standard time, using this helpful converter, 5am to 12pm UTC is equivalent to 12am to 7am EST. Since a large portion of the user base of Wikipedia is from the United States, it would make sense that the least activity occurs in the middle of the night, and the most activity occurs during the daytime hours or evening.

Tidying categories¶

In the original dataset, the categories field for a single row consists of a space-separated list of categories for the article for that row. This is not tidy, as we want to be able to deal with individual categories. We need to modify the data so that each row has only one of the categories that belong to it. This will add duplication to the data, as the rest of the row will be duplicated for each of its categories, but it will make the data easier to analyze. The same will be done for the list of external links (the column named "external").

The needed operation is the "explode" operation, which does exactly what is described above for a specified column. It takes a list of values, and makes individual rows for each value in the list, duplicating the other fields in the row.

Before using the explode operation, we must first convert the item to a list structure by splitting on the spaces. Then, we simply call Pandas's explode function, specifying the column name. Documentation for the explode function can be found here: https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.explode.html

In [20]:
# First, remove the extra space that is at the beginning
df["CATEGORY"] = df["CATEGORY"].str.slice(1) 

# Then, split the string by spaces
df["CATEGORY"] = df["CATEGORY"].str.split(" ")

Tidying external links¶

We will also want to analyze the different external links that an article links to. We will do a similar operation as we did with the category column.

Rather than keeping the entire website that is linked to, we'll just focus on the domain part of the URL (e.g. www.example.com rather than www.example.com/sub/page). This will allow us to get a better picture of which websites in general are linked to, not caring about what specific page is linked to.

First, we will split the "external" column by spaces to get a list of the external links. Then, we will use the function urlparse from Python's urllib library to extract the domain from each link. Then, we will perform the explode operation to associate one domain per row, which will again duplicate the rest of the data so that we will still have access to the rest of the observation's fields.

In [26]:
# First, remove the extra space that is at the beginning
df["EXTERNAL"] = df["EXTERNAL"].str.slice(1) 

# Then, split the string by spaces
df["EXTERNAL"] = df["EXTERNAL"].str.split(" ")

# Function that takes a list of urls and returns a list of unique domains
def get_domains (url_list):
    domains = set()
    if np.all(pd.notnull(url_list)):
        for url in url_list:
            try:
                domain = urlparse(url).netloc
            except ValueError:
                domain = np.nan
            domains.add(domain)
        #print(domains)    
    return list(domains)

Learning on the data¶

Preparing the links and categories for clustering¶

From here on, we will be focusing on making our website suggestion generator. Given a category for an article someone is working on, we should be able to generate a suggestion of a website to do research on.

One important part in accomplishing this task is the use of a clustering algorithm. A clustering algorithm will help us to form groups of similar categories. It is important to have groups of categories so that our website suggestion generator can provide useful suggestions. For instance, say that we are trying to suggest websites related to a particular category, but we only know of a few websites that are associated with that category. However, if we know what other categories are related to this category (because they are in the same category group), then we can suggest the websites associated with the similar categories.

We will be using the kmeans algorithm for clustering the categories. The kmeans algorithm groups together categories based on their similarity. In our case, similarity means that the categories have similar websites that they link to.

To this end, for each category, we will want a list of what websites articles in the category link to, and the frequency of how often each website is linked to. We will format this information in a data structure which we will then pass into the kmeans function of the sklearn library. The output of the kmeans function will tell us the groupings of categories that were generated.

First, we'll find the frequency of each website linked in each category.

In [33]:

Now, we want a table where each row represents one category, each column represents one website domain, and the value at each cell represents the number of times that the domain shows up in articles of that category.

To do so, we can use the Pandas unstack operation on the dataframe of categories and domains that we just created, which will form exactly the structure we want. (Here are examples of the unstack() function)

In [34]:

However, there's a problem with this. In order to represent all of the domains and categories that we have, this would form so large of a dataframe that Python will not be able to store it in memory.

To work around this, we can take advantage of one fact: out of all the possible domains in the dataset, any given category will only consist of some of them. In other words, for one category, a select portion of the domains will have values, while the remaining ones will all be zeroes.

This means that we can represent this data much more efficiently in a sparse matrix, which is a matrix where most values are zero. In a sparse matrix, only the non-zero values need to be stored in memory along with their row and column positions, while the remaining positions are implicitly zero. We will then be able to pass this sparse matrix into the kmeans function.

Fortunately, the scipy library has a data structure meant especially for this: the csr_matrix (compressed sparse row matrix). Read here to find more about this data structure: https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/generated/scipy.sparse.csr_matrix.html

To initialize a csr_matrix, we need to pass in three arrays: one array containing all of the values that we want to store, one array containing all of the row indicies for each value, and one array containing all of the column indicies for each value. See the link above for an example of what such input and output might look like.

In [35]:
# First, we create a list of all of the unique domains and categories in our data
all_domains = list(df["EXTERNAL"].unique())
all_categories = list(df["CATEGORY"].unique())
In [36]:
# Next, we create two dictionaries where the key is either the category or domain name, and
# the value is the index of that category or domain in the overall list.
# We do this so that we can access the correct row or column index for a category or domain in constant time,
# so we can efficiently build our sparse matrix.
all_domain_indicies = { all_domains[x] : x for x in range(len(all_domains)) }
all_category_indicies = { all_categories[x] : x for x in range(len(all_categories)) }

Our sparse matrix is now formed, and it all fits in memory (since we aren't storing lots of extra zeroes now)! We can now perform clustering on the data.

K-Means clustering to group together similar categories¶

We will now perform k-means clustering to create groupings of categories based on the similarity of the categories, where similarity is based on the particular domains that articles in the categories link to.

One consideration is our value of "k", which represents the number of groupings (called clusters) that the algorithm will generate. There's not a particular amount of groupings that we are looking for, so let's use a value of k=20, which seems reasonable and won't take very much computational time.

In [41]:
num_clusters = 20
kmeans_result = KMeans(n_clusters=num_clusters).fit(sparse_matrix)

# For each cluster, we want to aggregate the links for all categories in that cluster.
# The result should be a dictionary where the key is the cluster (as a set of category names),
# and the value is a dictionary of domain names with their frequencies.

cluster_links = defaultdict(lambda: defaultdict(int))
for cluster in clusters_list: # For each cluster
    cluster_set = frozenset(cluster) # create a frozenset so that we can use the set as a key in the dictionary
    for category in cluster: # For each category in this cluster
        if category in link_counts_by_cat: # If this is a category we have links for
            links = link_counts_by_cat[category] # Get all the links associated with this category
            
            for link, count in links.items(): # For each link
                if count > 0:
                    cluster_links[cluster_set][link] += count  # Add it to this cluster's list of links

def get_suggested_links(category_name):
    # First, identify which cluster this category belongs to.
    for cluster, links in cluster_links.items():
        if category_name in cluster: # We found the cluster for this category
            # return the list of links for this cluster
            return sorted(links.items(), key=lambda x : x[1], reverse=True)

Room for improvement¶

The above results look promising, however there are a few potential areas of improvement.

First of all, when asking for suggested links for a particular category, there are some websites that show up over and over again for many of the categories. For example, news.bbc.co.uk or nytimes.com show up under many categories with high frequencies. Although these are likely good sources for research for a particular category, they aren't the type of specific website suggestions that would make this model useful.

Secondly, the distribution of categories in the above clusters is heavily skewed, with only a few clusters containing a majority of the categories. A more accurate system should have clusters that more evenly divide the categories. This would mean that each cluster is specialized for a particular set of categories all having something in common, and thus providing a set of websites that would be useful under that umbrella of topics.

There's a possibility that solving the first issue might solve the second issue. One possibility for why the clusters are coming out so skewed could be that since many categories link to the most frequent domains, those categories are being grouped together based on that similarity. We instead want the categories to be grouped based on the websites that are more unique to those categories.

Clustering with inverse document frequency¶

Thus, we turn to the concept of inverse document frequency (IDF). This is a concept normally seen in contexts related to natural language processing (NLP). In that context, inverse document frequency is used to apply a lesser weight to words that show up in more documents. In other words, it puts more weight on the words that are more unique to each document and don't show up as much elsewhere, so that the key features of the document can stand out when performing NLP tasks. You can read more about inverse document frequency here: https://nlp.stanford.edu/IR-book/html/htmledition/inverse-document-frequency-1.html

In the context of our categories and websites, we would want to apply the concept of inverse document frequency to the websites for each category. To calculate the IDF for each website, we take the number of total categories and divide this number by the number of categories that link to this website, and then take the log of the whole expression. Then, for the website described for each category, we would multiply the IDF value for the particular frequency of this website in the category, to still incorporate the importance of this website for this particular category. In NLP, the equivalent concept is TF-IDF (term frequency, inverse document frequency)

$$ \text{weight value for website w in category c} = freq_{w,c} \cdot log{\frac{\text{# total categories}}{\text{# categories that link to w}}} $$

First, we will construct a dictionary where the key is the domain name, and the value is the number of categories that link to the domain.

sparse_matrix = csr_matrix((data, (rows, cols)))

Unfortunately, it doesn't seem like the implementation of inverse document frequency caused a large difference in the result. The distribution of categories in the clusters is still heavily skewed, and in fact more so than with our original attempt. Further investigation could reveal why this is the case, and what could be done to make a more even split of clusters. Perhaps the links in the categories simply aren't a good enough metric of the categories to be able to come up with meaningful groupings. Perhaps many categories don't have enough external links to be able to create meaningful associations. Or, perhaps a different curation of the data or a different algorithm could better formulate these categories in order to give meaningful suggestions for the broadest selection of categories.

For now, we can still do some analysis of some trends with the smaller category clusters that are evidently well-grouped.

Conclusion¶

As we've noted, the result of the kmeans clustering is far from perfect. However, we've demonstrated that there is potential in grouping together categories based on external links, and generating insights from those groupings. Additionally, we've prototyped a system for generating website suggestions for a certain category. This is the start of what could be a useful tool for someone who is contributing to a Wikipedia article and looking for relevant sources of information.

Further investigation would be needed to determine how to improve the result of the clustering. Perhaps a different way of representing the data would help. Or, maybe the results of the clustering were due to the way we sampled the original dataset, and using the full (8 GB!) dataset would have yielded better results.

Let's review what we've covered during this tutorial!

Data science concepts learned¶

  • Using the UNIX tool 'awk' for pre-processing
  • The Pandas explode() function for tidying
  • Sparse matrices to represent data
  • K-means clustering
  • Using inverse document frequency

Overall lessons learned¶

  • Sometimes you put a lot of time and energy into something, and it doesn't turn out the way you were hoping. But you still learn a lot along the way!
  • The main goal here was to create a generator of website suggestions. It was relatively simple to create the infrastructure of being able to provide a list of websites, given a category. But learning on the data to create better groupings of categories was the hard part! It can take significant thought and insight to determine how best to represent data to get meaningful results.
  • There are many ways to approach a problem, especially for a dataset with many parameters. If one path doesn't turn out well, some other path might. Further work on this project could look at one of these other paths and perhaps get different results.
